Value.value: The pasha’s word is law, and those who question it dig their own graves.
The Chainbreakers call it freedom. I call it treason wrapped in pretty words.
I’ve kept order in these streets for twenty years. I won’t see it undone by fools with ideals.
Mercy weakens a city. Discipline builds an empire.
The pasha rewards loyalty, and I have no intention of being poor.
The Chainbreakers think chains are the enemy. They’ve never seen what happens without them.
I serve Calimport as it is, not as dreamers wish it to be.
Every rebellion starts with a whisper. My job is to silence it before it becomes a shout.
They call me cruel. I call myself necessary. Someone must keep the peace when others chase fantasies.
The Full Moon flies their banners in the night. I make sure dawn finds only ashes.

Value.value: Law in Calimport’s like a net - full of holes, and I’m paid to look through ‘em.
You want justice? That’s sold three alleys over. Price changes daily.
Don’t start trouble and I won’t have to pretend to stop it.
Half the folk I arrest are back on the streets before I finish my shift.
Bribes? I call it hazard pay.
If you see a knife fight, walk the other way. If you don’t see it, that’s my problem.
The pasha says keep order. He didn’t say whose order.
You’d be amazed how light a conscience gets once the coin’s heavy.
I’ve seen more honest faces in the sewers than in the council hall.
Calimport never sleeps, which means neither do I. Lucky me.

value.0: The Threadmaidens are both expert artisans and fierce warriors.
Threadmaiden of the Vibrant Order of Dyers and Weavers

Value.value: The threads speak if you know how to listen, and I have listened all my life.
If you walk these halls with deceit, the dyes will stain you for weeks. I have seen it happen.
Every tapestry begins as a prayer, and every finished one is a testament to divine craft.
Outsiders think we are simple weavers. They learn quickly that we are also the wardens of sacred knowledge.
I have guarded the Great Loom during its quiet hours. Its silence carries more power than most spells I know.
The dyes here are not made from plants alone. Some come from stars that fell before Calimport was born.
If the Loom rejects you, step back. Forcing a thread only invites calamity.
My sisters and I defend this place because creation itself must be defended. Gond wills it.
My blade protects the Loom Halls, but my hands honor Gond through the colors I craft.
Honor the threads, respect the colors, and the Loom may show you wonders beyond mortal craft.

Value.value: The threads speak if you know how to listen, and I have listened all my life.
If you walk these halls with deceit, the dyes will stain you for weeks. I have seen it happen.
Every tapestry begins as a prayer, and every finished one is a testament to divine craft.
Outsiders think we are simple weavers. They learn quickly that we are also the wardens of sacred knowledge.
I have guarded the Great Loom during its quiet hours. Its silence carries more power than most spells I know.

My sisters and I defend this place because creation itself must be defended. Gond wills it.
My blade protects the Loom Halls, but my hands honor Gond through the colors I craft.
Honor the threads, respect the colors, and the Loom may show you wonders beyond mortal craft.

The Great Tapestry Loom dominates the heart of the Loom Halls, a towering construct of ancient teakwood and enchanted bronze, its arms spanning wider than a wagon and rising nearly to the hall's vaulted ceiling. Every inch of it is etched with runes in the flowing style of old Calimshan, each sigil part of a spell that hums faintly beneath the surface. Threads of raw arcane essence hang from its beams like luminous cobwebs, drifting with colors no mortal dye can produce.


Legends claim the Loom was woven into existence by a council of archmages who sought to record the world not through ink or memory, but through living fiber. With it, they crafted tapestries that told more than stories: they captured history, prophecy, and the pulse of magic itself. Some of the most famed works in Faerûn were born upon its frame, battle scenes that shift with the moonlight, maps that update themselves as kingdoms rise and fall, and portraits that breathe, speak, and warn.


The Loom's enchantments are said to be alive, choosing its weavers as much as they choose it. Those who approach with impure intentions find the threads twisting away from their hands, knotting into impossible snarls. But for the worthy, the Loom responds like an eager companion, guiding fingers, steadying breath, and whispering sparks of inspiration that border on divine revelation.


Though centuries old, it remains untouched by decay, its wood warm to the touch and its bronze gleaming as if newly forged. No one knows the full measure of its power. Some claim it can weave destinies, altering the lives of those depicted in its cloth. Others insist it can bind spirits, imprison memories, or reveal truths the gods have hidden.


In the Wizard Ward, the Great Tapestry Loom is revered as both artifact and oracle, an unblinking witness to the magic, ambition, and history of Calimport. Some say the Loom does not merely record the world. It shapes it.

The Loom Halls were founded more than six centuries ago during the height of Calimport's arcane flourishing. At that time the Wizard Ward was a patchwork of independent mage towers, each ruled by its own reclusive master. Rivalries between these towers often erupted into quiet sabotage or open magical duels, and the Pashas feared that ungoverned wizardry would one day ignite a war within the city walls.


To prevent disaster, a conclave of senior mages gathered under fragile truce. The gathering was later known as the Weavers Convergence. The mages sought a shared space where arcane craft could be practiced without endless competition. Their solution was to construct a neutral hall dedicated to the study of magical textile arts, rune weaving, and the containment of living spells. By choosing a discipline that combined artistry, enchantment, and meticulous control, they hoped to encourage cooperation and discourage destructive displays of power.


The foundation stone was laid by Master Alzahir Ithmarr, a renowned arcanist who specialized in binding magic into physical mediums. His designs shaped not only the structure of the Loom Halls but also its purpose. He taught that woven enchantments could stabilize volatile energies more safely than scrolls or crystals. A tapestry might store memories or bind elemental forces, yet remain inert until a spell keyed to its threads unraveled the pattern.


Construction of the Halls lasted more than a decade. Artificers from across Calimshan contributed carvings, sigils, and containment wards. When the building finally opened, it housed the earliest form of the Great Tapestry Loom. That first Loom was powerful, yet far simpler than the perfected artifact that stands there now. As the Halls earned prestige, new Looms were added, each an improvement of the last. Eventually the greatest archmages combined their patterncraft to build the masterwork that would become the Great Tapestry Loom.


Over time, the Loom Halls evolved into a sanctuary for scholars, weavers, historians, and visionary mages. The Halls produced tapestries that chronicled wars, captured illusions, and sealed wayward spirits. Apprentices from noble and common families alike fought for the chance to study within its chambers. Although political tensions still simmered in the Wizard Ward, the Loom Halls remained largely untouched thanks to its reputation for neutral stewardship and its importance to Calimport's magical stability.


Even now the Halls function as the intellectual heart of the Ward. Their Looms are treated not only as tools of craft, but as living archives of Calimport's past. The oldest weavings still whisper faint echoes of the Convergence, and some say the Loom Halls themselves remember every spell ever threaded within their walls.

The Order of the Crouching Lemur are a monastic group who espouse endurance and strength of spirit in the face of adversity, and prove this by eking out an existence on a harsh mountain in the Skull Crags, beset on all sides by the environment and hostile creatures.

Despite their isolationist ways, they are surprisingly welcoming to outsiders, offering fine wares and supplies to those who can provide the coin. It isn't uncommon to find these robes in place as far as Brogendenstein, and this open nature has helped spread the word of the relatively small monastery across the land.

Stories speak of a poor traveller, victim to a snowstorm one winter night. In the midst of frostbite and unconsciousness, he stumbled upon an isolated monastery, dedicated to Ilmater. The monks took him in, gave him shelter, food and most notably, a pair of thick, snow-wading boots.

With new-found vigor, he left the next day, boots firmly clad. Winter gave way to spring, and spring gave way to further winters, until the man was wealthy enough to return to that secluded monastery, to give his thanks for supporting him at his time of need.

To his surprise, he could not find the monastery, no matter how hard he searched the land. The blizzard returned once more during his searches, covering the land in a white blanket. One quiet night resting in his makeshift shelter, he found a dying man, frozen half to death. After feeding him and nursing him to health, he gifted the man those same boots he received years prior, and decided to build a small monastery in place of the one he could no longer find.

To his surprise, he could not find the monastery, no matter how hard he searched the land. The blizzard returned once more during his searches, covering the land in a white blanket.
